              <h3>2. Dark Mode & High Contrast Design</h3>
              <p>Dark mode isn't just a trend - it's an accessibility feature. More users prefer dark interfaces, especially on mobile devices. Modern websites should offer toggle options or automatically detect system preferences.</p>

              <h3>3. Micro-Interactions & Motion Design</h3>
              <p>Subtle animations that respond to user actions (like button hovers, scroll effects, and loading states) create engaging experiences without overwhelming visitors. Tools like Framer Motion and GSAP make these achievable on any platform.</p>

              <h3>4. Mobile-First is Now Mobile-Only</h3>
              <p>With over 65% of Australian web traffic coming from mobile devices, designing for mobile isn't optional - it's the starting point. Google's mobile-first indexing means your mobile site IS your primary site for SEO purposes.</p>

              <h3>5. Voice Search Optimisation</h3>
              <p>Smart speakers and voice assistants are changing how people search. Websites need to be optimised for conversational queries like "Where's the best dentist near Bella Vista?" rather than just "dentist Bella Vista".</p>

              <h3>6. Minimalist Navigation & Mega Menus</h3>
              <p>Clean, intuitive navigation with well-organised mega menus helps users find what they need faster. The trend is moving away from cluttered sidebars toward focused, purposeful layouts.</p>

              <h3>7. Sustainability-Focused Design</h3>
              <p>Eco-conscious design reduces page weight, optimises images, and minimises server requests - good for the planet and for your loading times. Sustainable web design is becoming a competitive advantage.</p>

